SIMPLE: initiate
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Initiate
<hw>In*i"ti*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Initiated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Initiating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>initiatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>initiare</ets> to begin, fr.
<ets>initium</ets> beginning. See <er>Initial</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To introduce by a first act; to make a beginning
with; to set afoot; to originate; to commence; to begin or enter
upon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How are changes of this sort to be <qex>initiated</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To acquaint with the beginnings; to instruct in the
rudiments or principles; to introduce.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Providence would only <qex>initiate</qex> mankind into the useful
knowledge of her treasures, leaving the rest to employ our industry.</q>
<rj><qau>Dr. H. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>initiate</qex> his pupil into any part of learning, an
ordinary skill in the governor is enough.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To introduce into a society or organization; to
confer membership on; especially, to admit to a secret order with
mysterious rites or ceremonies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Athenians believed that he who was <qex>initiated</qex> and
instructed in the mysteries would obtain celestial honor after
death.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Warburton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was <qex>initiated</qex> into half a dozen clubs before he was
one and twenty.</q> <rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Initiate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Initiate
<hw>In*i"ti*ate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To do the first act; to
perform the first rite; to take the initiative.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Initiate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Initiate
<hw>In*i"ti*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>initiatus</ets>, p. p.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Unpracticed; untried; new.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>initiate</xex> fear that wants hard use.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Begun; commenced; introduced to, or instructed in,
the rudiments; newly admitted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To rise in science as in bliss,⟦br⟧
<qex>Initiate</qex> in the secrets of the skies.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Initiate tenant by courtesy</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>,
<cd>said of a husband who becomes such in his wife's estate of
inheritance by the birth of a child, but whose estate is not consummated
till the death of the wife.</cd> <rj><au>Mozley & W.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Initiate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Initiate
<hw>In*i"ti*ate</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who is, or is to be,
initiated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Initiation</ent>⟦br⟧
